Here are the public test cases for feature10_available_kind:
{
  "description": "Determines whether a specific kind is available for a given apiVersion across a collection of cluster catalogs, where each catalog advertises a fixed set of kinds for one version. A kind is available only when some catalog both handles that apiVersion's shape and lists that kind; a kind listed under a different version, or not listed at all, is unavailable. Each query prints an 'api_version=... kind=... available=' line.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "available_kind",
        "catalogs": [
          {
            "style": "core",
            "group_version": "v1",
            "kinds": [
              "Pod",
              "CronJob"
            ]
          },
          {
            "style": "regular",
            "group_version": "app/v1",
            "kinds": [
              "Deployment",
              "Service"
            ]
          }
        ],
        "queries": [
          {
            "api_version": "v1",
            "kind": "Pod"
          },
          {
            "api_version": "app/v1",
            "kind": "Service"
          },
          {
            "api_version": "v1",
            "kind": "Deployment"
          },
          {
            "api_version": "app/v1",
            "kind": "CronJob"
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "api_version=v1 kind=Pod available=true\napi_version=app/v1 kind=Service available=true\napi_version=v1 kind=Deployment available=false\napi_version=app/v1 kind=CronJob available=false\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature10_validate_manifest:
{
  "description": "Validates every resource document in a manifest file against a collection of cluster catalogs, succeeding only when each document's kind is advertised for its apiVersion. A manifest whose single document's apiVersion/kind is advertised passes; a manifest whose apiVersion is unknown to all catalogs, or whose kind is listed only under a different version, is rejected with 'error=resource_not_available' together with the offending kind and apiVersion.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "validate_manifest_availability",
        "catalogs": [
          {
            "style": "core",
            "group_version": "v1",
            "kinds": [
              "Pod",
              "CronJob"
            ]
          },
          {
            "style": "regular",
            "group_version": "app/v1",
            "kinds": [
              "Deployment",
              "Service"
            ]
          }
        ],
        "manifest": "---\napiVersion: app/v1\nkind: Service\nmetadata:\n  name: my-service\nspec:\n  ports:\n  - name: HTTP\n    port: 80\n    protocol: TCP\n    targetPort: 80\n  selector:\n    app: my-app\n  type: ClusterIP\n"
      },
      "expected_output": "available=true\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature1_dictionary_merge:
{
  "description": "Deeply merges two configuration mappings into one. Keys present only in the override win; keys present in both are combined recursively when both values are mappings, otherwise the override value replaces the base value entirely (including replacing a mapping with a scalar, or replacing a list rather than concatenating it). The base input is never mutated.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "merge",
        "base": {
          "name": "app",
          "ports": [
            80,
            443
          ],
          "labels": {
            "team": "core"
          },
          "replicas": {
            "min": 1
          }
        },
        "override": {
          "name": "web",
          "ports": [
            8080
          ],
          "labels": {
            "tier": "frontend"
          },
          "replicas": 3
        }
      },
      "expected_output": "{\n  \"labels\": {\n    \"team\": \"core\",\n    \"tier\": \"frontend\"\n  },\n  \"name\": \"web\",\n  \"ports\": [\n    8080\n  ],\n  \"replicas\": 3\n}"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature2_config_section_errors:
{
  "description": "Loads a named section from a YAML configuration document and reports structural errors as neutral categories instead of raising. The loader rejects a missing configuration file, a file whose parsed content is empty, a file that is not valid YAML, a request for a section name that does not exist, and a section that (after being merged with the shared 'common' section) declares neither a 'templates' nor a 'kubectl' list of items to deploy. It also rejects an empty section name, and the reserved shared section name that exists only to be inherited and is never deployed on its own. Each case prints a single 'error=<category>' line identifying which rule was violated.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "resolve",
        "section": "section",
        "no_config": true
      },
      "expected_output": "error=config_not_found\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_include_loop:
{
  "description": "Detects a cyclic file='<path>' include chain while resolving a section and aborts instead of recursing forever. A value that, directly or transitively through nested includes, references a file that has already been visited on the current include path is rejected. The case wires two include files that reference each other and prints 'error=include_loop'.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "resolve",
        "section": "section_3",
        "aux_files": {
          "incorrect_include.yaml": "\n---\nincluded_file: \"{{ file='incorrect_include2.yaml' }}\"\n",
          "incorrect_include2.yaml": "\n---\nincluded_file: \"{{ file='incorrect_include.yaml' }}\"\n"
        },
        "config": "common:\n  k8s_namespace: namespace\nsection_3:\n  var: \"{{ file='incorrect_include.yaml' }}\"\n  templates:\n    - template: template1.yaml.j2\n"
      },
      "expected_output": "error=include_loop\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_recursive_substitution:
{
  "description": "Walks an arbitrary nested structure (mappings, lists, and scalars) and substitutes string placeholders in place, leaving non-string leaves untouched. Each string is scanned for an env='<NAME>' placeholder that is replaced by the environment variable value (an unset variable expands to empty text in non-strict mode), and for a file='<path>' placeholder that is replaced by the parsed YAML content of the referenced file. Numbers, booleans, and list ordering are preserved exactly, and a bare scalar passed in alone is returned unchanged. Output is the transformed structure as sorted JSON.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "update_context",
        "env": {
          "CUSTOM_ENV": "My value"
        },
        "aux_files": {
          "include.yaml": "---\nha_ha: \"included_var\"\n"
        },
        "context": {
          "section1": {
            "subsection1": {
              "section1-key1": "value",
              "section1-key2": 1,
              "section1-key3": 0.1,
              "section1-key4": [
                0,
                1,
                2,
                3
              ],
              "section1-key5": "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}",
              "section1-key6": "{{ file='include.yaml' }}",
              "section1-key7": "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV'}} = {{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}",
              "section1-key8": "{{ env='NULL_VAR' }}-{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}"
            }
          },
          "section2": [
            {},
            "var2",
            "var3",
            "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}",
            "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }} = {{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}",
            "{{ env='NULL_VAR' }}-{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}"
          ],
          "section3": [
            0,
            1,
            2,
            3,
            4
          ]
        }
      },
      "expected_output": "{\n  \"section1\": {\n    \"subsection1\": {\n      \"section1-key1\": \"value\",\n      \"section1-key2\": 1,\n      \"section1-key3\": 0.1,\n      \"section1-key4\": [\n        0,\n        1,\n        2,\n        3\n      ],\n      \"section1-key5\": \"My value\",\n      \"section1-key6\": {\n        \"ha_ha\": \"included_var\"\n      },\n      \"section1-key7\": \"My value = My value\",\n      \"section1-key8\": \"-My value\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"section2\": [\n    {},\n    \"var2\",\n    \"var3\",\n    \"My value\",\n    \"My value = My value\",\n    \"-My value\"\n  ],\n  \"section3\": [\n    0,\n    1,\n    2,\n    3,\n    4\n  ]\n}"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_root_dashes:
{
  "description": "Validates that root-level variable names in a resolved section contain no dashes, because dashes are not legal identifiers for templating. Only top-level keys are checked; dashes nested inside mapping values are permitted. A section whose merged root keys include one or more dashed names is rejected with 'error=root_dashes' followed by the offending names in sorted order, while a section whose dashes appear only in nested values resolves successfully to a sorted JSON object.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "resolve",
        "section": "not_allowed",
        "aux_files": {
          "include.yaml": "---\nha_ha: \"included_var\"\n"
        },
        "config": "common:\n  my_file: \"{{ file='include.yaml' }}\"\n  k8s_namespace: namespace\n  templates:\n    - template: template1.yaml.j2\nnot_allowed:\n  my-var: my_value\n  my-var-with-dashes: not allowed\n"
      },
      "expected_output": "error=root_dashes\nvars=my-var, my-var-with-dashes\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_strict_env_unset:
{
  "description": "When strict environment resolution is enabled, expanding a placeholder env='<NAME>' for an environment variable that is not set is treated as a hard error rather than substituting empty text. The rule applies to placeholders found directly in a section's values, in values pulled in through a file='<path>' include, and through chains of nested includes. Each case enables strict mode with the referenced variable unset and prints 'error=env_not_set' together with the offending variable name.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "resolve",
        "section": "section_1",
        "strict": true,
        "config": "common:\n  k8s_namespace: namespace\nsection_1:\n  var: \"{{ env='SECTION1' }}\"\n  templates:\n    - template: template1.yaml.j2\n"
      },
      "expected_output": "error=env_not_set\nvar=SECTION1\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_variable_resolution:
{
  "description": "Resolves a configuration section by overlaying it on the shared 'common' section and expanding string placeholders. A placeholder of the form file='<path>' is replaced by the parsed YAML content of that file (yielding a nested mapping), and a placeholder of the form env='<NAME>' is replaced by the value of that environment variable; literal text surrounding an env placeholder is preserved so placeholders can be concatenated with prefixes/suffixes or with each other. Section values override common values, while mappings present in both are merged recursively. The output is the fully resolved section as a sorted JSON object.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "resolve",
        "section": "test_dirs",
        "env": {
          "CUSTOM_ENV": "My value"
        },
        "aux_files": {
          "include.yaml": "---
ha_ha: "included_var"
"
        },
        "config": "common:
  my_var: my_value
  my_file: "{{ file='include.yaml' }}"
  my_env_var: "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}"
test_dirs:
  dirs:
    - dst: /tmp/test_directory1/
  templates:
    - template: template1.yaml.j2
"
      },
      "expected_output": "{
  "dirs": [
    {
      "dst": "/tmp/test_directory1/"
    }
  ],
  "my_env_var": "My value",
  "my_file": {
    "ha_ha": "included_var"
  },
  "my_var": "my_value",
  "templates": [
    {
      "template": "template1.yaml.j2"
    }
  ]
}"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature4_render_errors:
{
  "description": "Reports rendering failures as neutral error categories. Asking the engine to render from a null context is rejected with 'error=none_context'. A section that resolves with no usable template items prints 'error=no_template_items'. Referencing a template file that does not exist (including a name that is an unmatchable/invalid pattern, which is then treated as a literal name) prints 'error=template_not_found' with the missing template name. Rendering a template that references an undefined variable under strict-undefined semantics prints 'error=undefined_variable' with the variable name.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "render",
        "raw_context": null,
        "templates_files": {
          "template1.yaml.j2": "{{ x }}"
        },
        "config": "common: {}\n"
      },
      "expected_output": "error=none_context\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature4_render_templates:
{
  "description": "Renders the templates declared by a resolved configuration section into output files, returning each produced file's relative path and rendered content. Template items may be listed under a 'templates' key or, equivalently, under a 'kubectl' key; items may be nested inside arbitrarily deep 'group' wrappers and are flattened; and a template name that is a regular expression is expanded to every available template file whose name it matches. Each context variable is available to the template engine, an include placeholder resolves to a nested mapping rendered with its native text form, a value piped through the base64-encode filter is encoded, a literal piped through the base64-decode filter is decoded, a static-file include global splices in the indented contents of matching files, and a list-files global yields the sorted base names of matching files. Output lists files in sorted path order, each introduced by a '# file:' header.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "render",
        "section": "test_dirs",
        "env": {
          "CUSTOM_ENV": "My value"
        },
        "aux_files": {
          "include.yaml": "---
ha_ha: "included_var"
",
          "templates_tests/my_file.txt": "{{ hello world }}
new
line
",
          "templates_tests/my_file1.txt": "{{ hello world1 }}",
          "templates_tests/innerdir/template1.yaml.j2": "{{ my_file }}"
        },
        "templates_files": {
          "template1.yaml.j2": "{{ my_file }}",
          "template2.yaml.j2": "{{ my_env_var | b64encode }}
",
          "template3.yaml.j2": "{{ 'TXkgdmFsdWU=' | b64decode }}
",
          "template_include_file.yaml.j2": "test: |
  {{ include_file('templates_tests/my_file*.txt') | indent(2) }}
",
          "innerdir/template1.yaml.j2": "{{ my_file }}",
          "template_list_files.yaml.j2": "test: |
  {% for f in list_files('templates_tests/innerdir') -%}
  {{ f.split('/')[-1] }}:
  {% endfor -%}
  {% for f in list_files('templates_tests/my_file*.txt') -%}
  {{ f.split('/')[-1] }}:
  {% endfor -%}
"
        },
        "config": "common:
  my_var: my_value
  my_file: "{{ file='include.yaml' }}"
  my_env_var: "{{ env='CUSTOM_ENV' }}"
test_dirs:
  dirs:
    - dst: /tmp/test_directory1/
  templates:
    - template: template1.yaml.j2
    - template: template2.yaml.j2
    - template: template3.yaml.j2
    - template: template_include_file.yaml.j2
    - template: innerdir/template1.yaml.j2
    - template: template_list_files.yaml.j2
"
      },
      "expected_output": "# file: innerdir/template1.yaml
{'ha_ha': 'included_var'}
# file: template1.yaml
{'ha_ha': 'included_var'}
# file: template2.yaml
TXkgdmFsdWU=
# file: template3.yaml
My value
# file: template_include_file.yaml
test: |
  {{ hello world }}
  new
  line

  {{ hello world1 }}
# file: template_list_files.yaml
test: |
  template1.yaml.j2:
  my_file.txt:
  my_file1.txt:

"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature5_evaluate_tags:
{
  "description": "Decides whether a template that carries a set of tags should be included given an optional allow-list ('only') and an optional skip-list ('skip'). A template is excluded when an allow-list is given and the template shares no tag with it, and excluded when a skip-list is given and the template shares any tag with it; otherwise it is included. When no lists are given the template is always included, and these rules also hold when the template has no tags at all. Each evaluation prints a 'match=true' or 'match=false' line in order.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "eval_tags",
        "evaluations": [
          {
            "tags": [
              "tag1",
              "tag2",
              "tag3"
            ],
            "only": [
              "tag1"
            ],
            "skip": null
          },
          {
            "tags": [
              "tag1",
              "tag2",
              "tag3"
            ],
            "only": [
              "tag4"
            ],
            "skip": null
          },
          {
            "tags": [
              "tag1",
              "tag2",
              "tag3"
            ],
            "only": [
              "tag1"
            ],
            "skip": [
              "tag1"
            ]
          },
          {
            "tags": [
              "tag1",
              "tag2",
              "tag3"
            ],
            "only": null,
            "skip": [
              "tag1"
            ]
          },
          {
            "tags": [
              "tag1",
              "tag2",
              "tag3"
            ],
            "only": null,
            "skip": [
              "tag4"
            ]
          },
          {
            "tags": [],
            "only": [
              "tag4"
            ],
            "skip": null
          },
          {
            "tags": [],
            "only": null,
            "skip": [
              "tag4"
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "match=true\nmatch=false\nmatch=false\nmatch=false\nmatch=true\nmatch=false\nmatch=true\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature5_parse_tags:
{
  "description": "Normalizes the tags attached to a template item into a set. Tags provided as a list become the set of distinct entries, and tags provided as a single comma-separated string are split on commas into a set; a one-element list and a single bare string each yield a single-tag set. Supplying tags of any other type is rejected with 'error=unexpected_tags_type'. Each parsed result prints a 'tags=' line with the members in sorted order.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "parse_tags",
        "inputs": [
          [
            "tag1",
            "tag2",
            "tag3"
          ],
          "tag1,tag2,tag3",
          [
            "tag1"
          ],
          "tag1"
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "tags=tag1,tag2,tag3\ntags=tag1,tag2,tag3\ntags=tag1\ntags=tag1\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature6_client_configuration:
{
  "description": "Assembles a Kubernetes client configuration from CLI, context, and environment inputs by precedence, requiring both a master URI and a token. A missing master URI is rejected with 'error=missing_master_uri' and a missing token with 'error=missing_token'. On success it reports the host (master URI), the bearer authorization header built from the token, whether debug is enabled (a debug flag supplied through the context as a truthy string turns it on), and the decoded certificate-authority text obtained by base64-decoding the supplied CA value.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "client_configuration",
        "cli": {
          "k8s_ca_base64": "value_cli",
          "k8s_token": "value_cli"
        }
      },
      "expected_output": "error=missing_master_uri\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature6_env_deprecated:
{
  "description": "Detects whether legacy/deprecated environment variables are present for supplying the cluster master URI or certificate authority. The check is true when either deprecated variable holds a non-empty value and false when both are absent or empty. Each environment set prints a 'deprecated=true' or 'deprecated=false' line.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "env_deprecated",
        "env_sets": [
          {
            "K8S_CA": "value_env_deprecated"
          },
          {
            "K8S_HOST": "value_env_deprecated"
          },
          {
            "K8S_CA": ""
          },
          {
            "K8S_HOST": ""
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "deprecated=true\ndeprecated=true\ndeprecated=false\ndeprecated=false\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature6_first_truthy:
{
  "description": "Picks the first 'truthy' value from an ordered argument list, modeling configuration precedence where higher-priority sources are listed first. Falsy values (none, false, zero, empty string, empty mapping, empty list) are skipped, and if every argument is falsy or there are no arguments the result is 'none'. Each argument set prints a 'first=' line with the selected value or 'none'.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "first_truthy",
        "arg_sets": [
          [],
          [
            null
          ],
          [
            null,
            false,
            0,
            "",
            {},
            []
          ],
          [
            "value_cli",
            "value_env"
          ],
          [
            "",
            "value_env"
          ]
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "first=none\nfirst=none\nfirst=none\nfirst=value_cli\nfirst=value_env\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature6_namespace_default:
{
  "description": "Resolves the effective namespace by precedence: an explicit namespace from the configuration context wins over a namespace taken from a supplied kubeconfig default, which in turn wins over a namespace from the environment. When the context value is absent the kubeconfig default is used if provided, otherwise the environment value is used. Each scenario prints a 'namespace=' line with the resolved value or 'none'.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "namespace_default",
        "scenarios": [
          {
            "context": {
              "k8s_namespace": "value_context"
            },
            "env": {
              "K8S_NAMESPACE": "value_env"
            }
          },
          {
            "context": {
              "k8s_namespace": "value_context"
            },
            "env": {
              "K8S_NAMESPACE": "value_env"
            },
            "kubeconfig": "kubeconfig_namespace"
          },
          {
            "context": {},
            "env": {
              "K8S_NAMESPACE": "value_env"
            }
          },
          {
            "context": {},
            "env": {
              "K8S_NAMESPACE": "value_env"
            },
            "kubeconfig": "kubeconfig_namespace"
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "namespace=value_context\nnamespace=value_context\nnamespace=value_env\nnamespace=kubeconfig_namespace\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature7_normalize_kind:
{
  "description": "Converts a Kubernetes resource kind written in CamelCase into a lower-cased, underscore-separated identifier, splitting at each capital letter so that a single-word kind becomes one lowercase word and a multi-word kind becomes underscore-joined words. Each input kind prints a 'name=' line with its normalized form.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "normalize_kind",
        "kinds": [
          "ConfigMap",
          "Namespace",
          "PodDisruptionBudget"
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "name=config_map\nname=namespace\nname=pod_disruption_budget\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature8_deprecation:
{
  "description": "Decides whether a given apiVersion/kind pair is deprecated relative to a server version, using a deprecation table that maps each apiVersion and kind to a 'since' version and an optional 'until' version. The pair is not deprecated when the apiVersion or the kind is absent from the table, or when the server version is below 'since'. It is deprecated once the server version reaches or exceeds 'since', and also when an 'until' is set and the server version reaches or exceeds it (unsupported); an empty 'until' is ignored. Comparisons are semantic-version aware and boundary-inclusive. Each case prints the apiVersion, kind, server version, and a 'deprecated=' boolean.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "check_deprecation",
        "server_version": "1.9.7",
        "api_version": "test/v2",
        "kind": "Deployment",
        "deprecations": {
          "test/v1": {
            "Deployment": {
              "since": "1.8.0",
              "until": "1.10.0"
            }
          }
        }
      },
      "expected_output": "api_version=test/v2\nkind=Deployment\nserver_version=1.9.7\ndeprecated=false\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature9_resources_by_version:
{
  "description": "Returns the set of resource kinds a cluster catalog advertises for a queried API group/version. When the queried version matches the catalog's version, the advertised kinds are returned; when it does not match, the empty set is returned. Each query prints a 'group=... kinds=...' line with the kinds in sorted, comma-separated order (empty when none).",
